{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_35","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"curl -sS 'https://websvc.biocyc.org/getxml?id=META:PWY-7550' | head -80\"","aggregated_output":"<?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"iso-8859-1\"?>\n<ptools-xml ptools-version='29.5' xml:base='http://BioCyc.org/getxml?META:PWY-7550'><metadata><url>http://BioCyc.org/</url>\n<service_name>getxml</service_name>\n<query>META:PWY-7550</query>\n<num_results>1</num_results>\n<PGDB orgid='META' version='29.6'><species datatype='string'>MetaCyc</species>\n</PGDB>\n</metadata>\n<Pathway ID='META:PWY-7550' orgid='META' frameid='PWY-7550' detail='full'><parent><Pathway resource='getxml?META:Ergothioneine-Biosynthesis' orgid='META' frameid='Ergothioneine-Biosynthesis' class='true'/></parent>\n<reaction-list><Reaction resource='getxml?META:RXN-18089' orgid='META' frameid='RXN-18089'/><Reaction resource='getxml?META:RXN-18088' orgid='META' frameid='RXN-18088'/><Reaction resource='getxml?META:RXN-15804' orgid='META' frameid='RXN-15804'/><Reaction resource='getxml?META:RXN-15801' orgid='META' frameid='RXN-15801'/><Reaction resource='getxml?META:RXN-14431' orgid='META' frameid='RXN-14431'/></reaction-list>\n<common-name datatype='string'>ergothioneine biosynthesis II (fungi)</common-name>\n<pathway-link><Compound resource='getxml?META:CYS' orgid='META' frameid='CYS'/><link-target><Pathway resource='getxml?META:PWY-6293' orgid='META' frameid='PWY-6293'/></link-target>\n</pathway-link>\n<pathway-link><Compound resource='getxml?META:HIS' orgid='META' frameid='HIS'/><link-target><Pathway resource='getxml?META:HISTSYN-PWY' orgid='META' frameid='HISTSYN-PWY'/></link-target>\n</pathway-link>\n<comment datatype='string'>&lt;b&gt;General Background&lt;/b&gt;\n&lt;p&gt;\n&lt;a href=&quot;/compound?orgid=META&amp;id=Ergothioneine&quot;&gt;Ergothioneine&lt;/a&gt; (EGT) is a histidine derivative with a thiol group attached to the C2 atom of the imidazole ring and a trimethylated amine. EGT was initially isolated in 1909 by Tanret from &lt;a href=&quot;/META/NEW-IMAGE?object=TAX-5111&quot;&gt;&lt;i&gt;Claviceps purpurea&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/a&gt; (ergot), the fungal infection of rye grain [&lt;a href=&quot;/META/reference.html?type=CITATION-REFERENCE&amp;object=%5bTanret09%5d&quot;&gt;Tanret09&lt;/a&gt;], and its structure was determined within two years [&lt;a href=&quot;http://xlink.rsc.org/?DOI=ct9119902336&quot;&gt;Barger11&lt;/a&gt;]. It has been reported only from certain fungi, actinomycetales bacteria and cyanobacteria [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/13376573&quot;&gt;Genghof56&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/13405916&quot;&gt;Melville57&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S0308814611009344&quot;&gt;Pfeiffer11&lt;/a&gt;]. The function of EGT in the microbial cells is not well understood, even though it is believed that EGT may protect cells from oxidative stress [&lt;a href=&quot;http://doi.wiley.com/10.1111/j.1399-3054.1956.tb07795.x&quot;&gt;Garay56&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2172707&quot;&gt;Hartman90&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22001064&quot;&gt;Cheah12&lt;/a&gt;].\n&lt;p&gt;\nThe most significant difference between EGT and other biological thiols is the instability of the EGT disulfide under physiological conditions. Unlike other small thiols such as &lt;a href=&quot;/compound?orgid=META&amp;id=GLUTATHIONE&quot;&gt;glutathione&lt;/a&gt;, EGT is stable in its reduced form in aerated aqueous solutions and does not form the disulfide [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15730267&quot;&gt;Hand05a&lt;/a&gt;]. Another significant difference is that EGT exists predominantly as the &lt;a href=&quot;/compound?orgid=META&amp;id=Ergothioneine-Thione&quot;&gt;thione form&lt;/a&gt; at physiological pH [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22001064&quot;&gt;Cheah12&lt;/a&gt;].\n&lt;p&gt;\nAlthough EGT is not synthesized by non-fungal eukaryotes, animals and plants acquire EGT from the environment through a specific transporter, ETT/OCTN1 [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15795384&quot;&gt;Grundemann05&lt;/a&gt;]. It has been shown that the human body absorbs it from dietary sources and concentrates it in specific tissues or cells such as liver, kidney, central nervous system, and red blood cells [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2172707&quot;&gt;Hartman90&lt;/a&gt;]. Both hyperactivity and deficiency of the OCTN1 transporter exert negative effects on human cells [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15795384&quot;&gt;Grundemann05&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19136526&quot;&gt;Taubert09&lt;/a&gt;]. The precise function of ergothioneine in human tissue is also uncertain [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17616140&quot;&gt;Ey07&lt;/a&gt;].\n&lt;p&gt;\n&lt;b&gt;About This Pathway&lt;/b&gt;\n&lt;p&gt;\nThe biosynthesis of &lt;a href=&quot;/compound?orgid=META&amp;id=Ergothioneine&quot;&gt;ergothioneine&lt;/a&gt; in fungi has been studied mostly in &lt;a href=&quot;/META/NEW-IMAGE?object=TAX-5141&quot;&gt;&lt;i&gt;Neurospora crassa&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/a&gt; [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/13654346&quot;&gt;Melville59&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/13862898&quot;&gt;Askari62&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/5438052&quot;&gt;Reinhold70&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/4276459&quot;&gt;Ishikawa74&lt;/a&gt;] and in &lt;a href=&quot;/META/NEW-IMAGE?object=TAX-5111&quot;&gt;&lt;i&gt;Claviceps purpurea&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/a&gt; [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/13382810&quot;&gt;Heath56&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/13403896&quot;&gt;Wildy57&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/13522637&quot;&gt;Heath58&lt;/a&gt;].\nBiosynthesis starts with the triple methylation of &lt;a href=&quot;/compound?orgid=META&amp;id=HIS&quot;&gt;L-histidine&lt;/a&gt; via a S-adenosyl methionine (SAM)-dependent methyltransferase to &lt;a href=&quot;/compound?orgid=META&amp;id=CPD-15280&quot;&gt;hercynine&lt;/a&gt; (histidine betaine). The next step in the pathway requires O&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; and Fe&lt;sup&gt;2+&lt;/sup&gt; for the sulfoxidation of hercynine to &lt;a href=&quot;/compound?orgid=META&amp;id=CPD-15277&quot;&gt;S-(hercyn-2-yl)-L-cysteine S-oxide&lt;/a&gt; [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/5484456&quot;&gt;Ishikawa70&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/4276459&quot;&gt;Ishikawa74&lt;/a&gt;]. Finally, a pyridoxal phosphate-requiring enzyme converts &lt;a href=&quot;/compound?orgid=META&amp;id=CPD-15277&quot;&gt;S-(hercyn-2-yl)-L-cysteine S-oxide&lt;/a&gt; to EGT.\nThe bacterial pathway differs from the eukaryotic pathway, and includes two additional enzymes (see &lt;a href=&quot;/pathway?orgid=META&amp;id=PWY-7255&quot;&gt;ergothioneine biosynthesis I (bacteria)&lt;/a&gt;).\n&lt;p&gt;\nTThe first eukaryotic &lt;a href=&quot;/compound?orgid=META&amp;id=Ergothioneine&quot;&gt;ergothioneine&lt;/a&gt; (EGT) biosynthetic gene was identified in the fungus &lt;a href=&quot;/META/NEW-IMAGE?object=TAX-5141&quot;&gt;&lt;i&gt;Neurospora crassa&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/a&gt; by its similarity to bacterial EGT biosynthetic genes [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/24828577&quot;&gt;Pluskal14&lt;/a&gt;]. The &lt;a href=&quot;/gene?orgid=META&amp;id=G-34553&quot;&gt;egt-1&lt;/a&gt; gene encodes a multidomain protein: The  N-terminal domain encodes a SAM-dependent methyltransferase with homology to &lt;a href=&quot;/gene?orgid=META&amp;id=G-15978&quot;&gt;egtD&lt;/a&gt; from &lt;a href=&quot;/META/NEW-IMAGE?object=TAX-1772&quot;&gt;&lt;i&gt;Mycolicibacterium smegmatis&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/a&gt; (27% identity), and the C-terminal domain encodes a sulfatase with homology to the &lt;a href=&quot;/META/NEW-IMAGE?object=TAX-1772&quot;&gt;&lt;i&gt;Mycolicibacterium smegmatis&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;/gene?orgid=META&amp;id=G-15979&quot;&gt;egtB&lt;/a&gt;. The C-terminal domain contains the iron binding motif (HX3HXE) that is also present in &lt;a href=&quot;/gene?orgid=META&amp;id=G-15979&quot;&gt;egtB&lt;/a&gt; [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/24828577&quot;&gt;Pluskal14&lt;/a&gt;].\nThe second gene, &lt;a href=&quot;/gene?orgid=META&amp;id=G-34554&quot;&gt;egt-2&lt;/a&gt;, was identified in &lt;a href=&quot;/META/NEW-IMAGE?object=TAX-4896&quot;&gt;&lt;i&gt;Schizosaccharomyces pombe&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/a&gt; a few years later [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/24828577&quot;&gt;Pluskal14&lt;/a&gt;].</comment>\n<taxonomic-range><Organism ID='META:TAX-4751' orgid='META' frameid='TAX-4751' detail='full' class='true'><parent><Organism resource='getxml?META:TAX-33154' orgid='META' frameid='TAX-33154' class='true'/></parent>\n<common-name datatype='string'>Fungi</common-name>\n<synonym datatype='string'>Mycota</synonym>\n<rank>kingdom</rank>\n<dblink><dblink-db>NCBI-TAXONOMY-DB</dblink-db>\n<dblink-oid>4751</dblink-oid>\n<dblink-relationship>unification</dblink-relationship>\n<dblink-URL>http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/Taxonomy/Browser/wwwtax.cgi?mode=Info&amp;id=4751</dblink-URL>\n</dblink>\n</Organism>\n</taxonomic-range>\n<credits><created><date datatype='date'>2014-08-19</date>\n<Person ID='META:caspi' orgid='META' frameid='caspi' detail='full'><common-name datatype='string'>Ron Caspi</common-name>\n<email datatype='string'>ron.caspi@sri.com</email>\n<comment datatype='string'>Ron Caspi received his PhD in Marine Microbiology in 1996 from the Scripps Institution of Oceanography in La Jolla, CA, under the guidance of Dr. Bradley Tebo and Dr. Margo Haygood. He completed his post-graduate education in 1999 with Dr. Donald Helinski at the Center for Molecular Genetics at UC San Diego. \n&lt;p&gt;\nAfter three years with Pangene Corporation, where he managed the automation and bioinformatics department, Ron joined SRI International in 2004, and has been the head curator of the MetaCyc database ever since.</comment>\n<affiliations><Organization ID='META:SRI' orgid='META' frameid='SRI' detail='full'><common-name datatype='string'>SRI International</common-name>\n<email datatype='string'>ptools-support@ai.sri.com</email>\n<abbrev-name datatype='string'>SRI International</abbrev-name>\n<url datatype='string'>http://bioinformatics.ai.sri.com/</url>\n</Organization>\n</affiliations>\n</Person>\n<Organization resource='#META:SRI' orgid='META' frameid='SRI'/></created>\n</credits>\n<reaction-layout><Reaction resource='getxml?META:RXN-18089' orgid='META' frameid='RXN-18089'/><direction>L2R</direction>\n<left-primaries><Compound resource='getxml?META:CPD-19388' orgid='META' frameid='CPD-19388'/></left-primaries>\n<right-primaries><Compound resource='getxml?META:Ergothioneine' orgid='META' frameid='Ergothioneine'/></right-primaries>\n</reaction-layout>\n<reaction-layout><Reaction resource='getxml?META:RXN-18088' orgid='META' frameid='RXN-18088'/><direction>L2R</direction>\n<left-primaries><Compound resource='getxml?META:CPD-15277' orgid='META' frameid='CPD-15277'/></left-primaries>\n<right-primaries><Compound resource='getxml?META:CPD-19388' orgid='META' frameid='CPD-19388'/></right-primaries>\n</reaction-layout>\n<reaction-layout><Reaction resource='getxml?META:RXN-15804' orgid='META' frameid='RXN-15804'/><direction>R2L</direction>\n<left-primaries><Compound resource='getxml?META:Ergothioneine-Thione' orgid='META' frameid='Ergothioneine-Thione'/></left-primaries>\n<right-primaries><Compound resource='getxml?META:Ergothioneine' orgid='META' frameid='Ergothioneine'/></right-primaries>\n</reaction-layout>\n<reaction-layout><Reaction resource='getxml?META:RXN-15801' orgid='META' frameid='RXN-15801'/><direction>L2R</direction>\n<left-primaries><Compound resource='getxml?META:CYS' orgid='META' frameid='CYS'/><Compound resource='getxml?META:CPD-15280' orgid='META' frameid='CPD-15280'/></left-primaries>\n<right-primaries><Compound resource='getxml?META:CPD-15277' orgid='META' frameid='CPD-15277'/></right-primaries>\n</reaction-layout>\n<reaction-layout><Reaction resource='getxml?META:RXN-14431' orgid='META' frameid='RXN-14431'/><direction>L2R</direction>\n<left-primaries><Compound resource='getxml?META:HIS' orgid='META' frameid='HIS'/></left-primaries>\n<right-primaries><Compound resource='getxml?META:CPD-15280' orgid='META' frameid='CPD-15280'/></right-primaries>\n</reaction-layout>\n<reaction-ordering><Reaction resource='getxml?META:RXN-15804' orgid='META' frameid='RXN-15804'/><predecessor-reactions><Reaction resource='getxml?META:RXN-18089' orgid='META' frameid='RXN-18089'/></predecessor-reactions>\n</reaction-ordering>\n<reaction-ordering><Reaction resource='getxml?META:RXN-18089' orgid='META' frameid='RXN-18089'/><predecessor-reactions><Reaction resource='getxml?META:RXN-18088' orgid='META' frameid='RXN-18088'/></predecessor-reactions>\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_33","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"curl -sS 'https://websvc.biocyc.org/getxml?id=META:PWY-7255' | head -80\"","aggregated_output":"<?xml version=\"1.0\" encoding=\"iso-8859-1\"?>\n<ptools-xml ptools-version='29.5' xml:base='http://BioCyc.org/getxml?META:PWY-7255'><metadata><url>http://BioCyc.org/</url>\n<service_name>getxml</service_name>\n<query>META:PWY-7255</query>\n<num_results>1</num_results>\n<PGDB orgid='META' version='29.6'><species datatype='string'>MetaCyc</species>\n</PGDB>\n</metadata>\n<Pathway ID='META:PWY-7255' orgid='META' frameid='PWY-7255' detail='full'><parent><Pathway resource='getxml?META:Ergothioneine-Biosynthesis' orgid='META' frameid='Ergothioneine-Biosynthesis' class='true'/></parent>\n<reaction-list><Reaction resource='getxml?META:RXN-18089' orgid='META' frameid='RXN-18089'/><Reaction resource='getxml?META:RXN-18088' orgid='META' frameid='RXN-18088'/><Reaction resource='getxml?META:RXN-15804' orgid='META' frameid='RXN-15804'/><Reaction resource='getxml?META:GLUTCYSLIG-RXN' orgid='META' frameid='GLUTCYSLIG-RXN'/><Reaction resource='getxml?META:RXN-14431' orgid='META' frameid='RXN-14431'/><Reaction resource='getxml?META:RXN-14430' orgid='META' frameid='RXN-14430'/><Reaction resource='getxml?META:RXN-14429' orgid='META' frameid='RXN-14429'/></reaction-list>\n<common-name datatype='string'>ergothioneine biosynthesis I (bacteria)</common-name>\n<pathway-link><Compound resource='getxml?META:CYS' orgid='META' frameid='CYS'/><link-target><Pathway resource='getxml?META:CYSTSYN-PWY' orgid='META' frameid='CYSTSYN-PWY'/></link-target>\n</pathway-link>\n<pathway-link><Compound resource='getxml?META:HIS' orgid='META' frameid='HIS'/><link-target><Pathway resource='getxml?META:HISTSYN-PWY' orgid='META' frameid='HISTSYN-PWY'/></link-target>\n</pathway-link>\n<comment datatype='string'>&lt;b&gt;General Background&lt;/b&gt;\n&lt;p&gt;\n&lt;a href=&quot;/compound?orgid=META&amp;id=Ergothioneine&quot;&gt;Ergothioneine&lt;/a&gt; (EGT) is a histidine derivative with a thiol group attached to the C2 atom of the imidazole ring and a trimethylated amine. EGT was initially isolated in 1909 by Tanret from &lt;a href=&quot;/META/NEW-IMAGE?object=TAX-5111&quot;&gt;&lt;i&gt;Claviceps purpurea&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/a&gt; (ergot), the fungal infection of rye grain [&lt;a href=&quot;/META/reference.html?type=CITATION-REFERENCE&amp;object=%5bTanret09%5d&quot;&gt;Tanret09&lt;/a&gt;], and its structure was determined within two years [&lt;a href=&quot;http://xlink.rsc.org/?DOI=ct9119902336&quot;&gt;Barger11&lt;/a&gt;]. It has been reported only from certain fungi, actinomycetales bacteria and cyanobacteria [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/13376573&quot;&gt;Genghof56&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/13405916&quot;&gt;Melville57&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S0308814611009344&quot;&gt;Pfeiffer11&lt;/a&gt;]. The function of EGT in the microbial cells is not well understood, even though it is believed that EGT may protect cells from oxidative stress [&lt;a href=&quot;http://doi.wiley.com/10.1111/j.1399-3054.1956.tb07795.x&quot;&gt;Garay56&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2172707&quot;&gt;Hartman90&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22001064&quot;&gt;Cheah12&lt;/a&gt;].\n&lt;p&gt;\nThe most significant difference between EGT and other biological thiols is the instability of the EGT disulfide under physiological conditions. Unlike other small thiols such as &lt;a href=&quot;/compound?orgid=META&amp;id=GLUTATHIONE&quot;&gt;glutathione&lt;/a&gt;, EGT is stable in its reduced form in aerated aqueous solutions and does not form the disulfide [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15730267&quot;&gt;Hand05a&lt;/a&gt;]. Another significant difference is that EGT exists predominantly as the &lt;a href=&quot;/compound?orgid=META&amp;id=Ergothioneine-Thione&quot;&gt;thione form&lt;/a&gt; at physiological pH [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22001064&quot;&gt;Cheah12&lt;/a&gt;].\n&lt;p&gt;\nAlthough EGT is not synthesized by non-fungal eukaryotes, animals and plants acquire EGT from the environment through a specific transporter, ETT/OCTN1 [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15795384&quot;&gt;Grundemann05&lt;/a&gt;]. It has been shown that the human body absorbs it from dietary sources and concentrates it in specific tissues or cells such as liver, kidney, central nervous system, and red blood cells [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/2172707&quot;&gt;Hartman90&lt;/a&gt;]. Both hyperactivity and deficiency of the OCTN1 transporter exert negative effects on human cells [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15795384&quot;&gt;Grundemann05&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/19136526&quot;&gt;Taubert09&lt;/a&gt;]. The precise function of ergothioneine in human tissue is also uncertain [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17616140&quot;&gt;Ey07&lt;/a&gt;].\n&lt;p&gt;\n&lt;b&gt;About This Pathway&lt;/b&gt;\n&lt;p&gt;\nEarly studies of the biosynthesis of &lt;a href=&quot;/compound?orgid=META&amp;id=Ergothioneine&quot;&gt;ergothioneine&lt;/a&gt;, carried out with cell-free extracts of &lt;a href=&quot;/META/NEW-IMAGE?object=TAX-5141&quot;&gt;&lt;i&gt;Neurospora crassa&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/a&gt;, demonstrated that it generated from &lt;a href=&quot;/compound?orgid=META&amp;id=HIS&quot;&gt;L-histidine&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;/compound?orgid=META&amp;id=CYS&quot;&gt;L-cysteine&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=&quot;/compound?orgid=META&amp;id=MET&quot;&gt;L-methionine&lt;/a&gt;, and the presence of several intermediates, namely &lt;a href=&quot;/compound?orgid=META&amp;id=CPD-15280&quot;&gt;hercynine&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=&quot;/compound?orgid=META&amp;id=CPD-15277&quot;&gt;S-(hercyn-2-yl)-L-cysteine S-oxide&lt;/a&gt; [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/5484456&quot;&gt;Ishikawa70&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/4276459&quot;&gt;Ishikawa74&lt;/a&gt;].\n&lt;p&gt;\nAdditional work revealed a gene cluster responsible for &lt;a href=&quot;/compound?orgid=META&amp;id=Ergothioneine&quot;&gt;ergothioneine&lt;/a&gt; biosynthesis in the genomes of mycobacteria [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20420449&quot;&gt;Seebeck10&lt;/a&gt;]. In mycobacteria 5 enzymatic steps are involved, catalyzed by the products of the &lt;a href=&quot;/gene?orgid=META&amp;id=G-15982&quot;&gt;egtA&lt;/a&gt; [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16262797&quot;&gt;Harth05&lt;/a&gt;], &lt;a href=&quot;/gene?orgid=META&amp;id=G-15978&quot;&gt;egtD&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;/gene?orgid=META&amp;id=G-15979&quot;&gt;egtB&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;/gene?orgid=META&amp;id=G-15980&quot;&gt;egtC&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=&quot;/gene?orgid=META&amp;id=G-15981&quot;&gt;egtE&lt;/a&gt; genes [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20420449&quot;&gt;Seebeck10&lt;/a&gt;]. The genes were cloned from &lt;a href=&quot;/META/NEW-IMAGE?object=TAX-1772&quot;&gt;&lt;i&gt;Mycolicibacterium smegmatis&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/a&gt; and were all purified and used for &lt;i&gt;in vitro&lt;/i&gt; characterization [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20420449&quot;&gt;Seebeck10&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/26149121&quot;&gt;Song15a&lt;/a&gt;]. The genes have also been identified in &lt;a href=&quot;/META/NEW-IMAGE?object=TAX-83332&quot;&gt;&lt;i&gt;Mycobacterium tuberculosis&lt;/i&gt; H37Rv&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;i&gt;egtD&lt;/i&gt; has been characterized from that organism as well [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/26229105&quot;&gt;RichardGreenbla15&lt;/a&gt;].\n&lt;p&gt;\nAnalysis of the distribution of &lt;a href=&quot;/gene?orgid=META&amp;id=G-15979&quot;&gt;egtB&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=&quot;/gene?orgid=META&amp;id=G-15978&quot;&gt;egtD&lt;/a&gt; suggests that ergothioneine biosynthesis is a common trait among actinobacteria, cyanobacteria, pezizomycotina, and basidiomycota, and also occurs in numerous bacteroidetes and &amp;alpha;-, &amp;beta;-, &amp;gamma;- and &amp;delta;-proteobacteria. This wide distribution suggests that ergothioneine may have fundamental physiological importance [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20420449&quot;&gt;Seebeck10&lt;/a&gt;].\n&lt;p&gt;\nIn fungi the EgtB and EgtD homologs are fused into a single protein [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/22209968&quot;&gt;Bello12&lt;/a&gt;] (see &lt;a href=&quot;/pathway?orgid=META&amp;id=PWY-7550&quot;&gt;ergothioneine biosynthesis II (fungi)&lt;/a&gt;).</comment>\n<taxonomic-range><Organism ID='META:TAX-28221' orgid='META' frameid='TAX-28221' detail='full' class='true'><parent><Organism resource='getxml?META:TAX-68525' orgid='META' frameid='TAX-68525' class='true'/></parent>\n<common-name datatype='string'>Deltaproteobacteria</common-name>\n<synonym datatype='string'>Sulfate-reducing or sulfur-reducing dissimilatory bacteria</synonym>\n<synonym datatype='string'>Sulfate- or sulfur-reducing dissimilatory bacteria</synonym>\n<synonym datatype='string'>Purple bacteria, delta subdivision</synonym>\n<synonym datatype='string'>Proteobacteria delta subdivision</synonym>\n<synonym datatype='string'>Dissimilatory sulfate or sulfur reducers</synonym>\n<synonym datatype='string'>delta subgroup</synonym>\n<synonym datatype='string'>delta subdivision</synonym>\n<synonym datatype='string'>delta proteobacteria</synonym>\n<synonym datatype='string'>Deltabacteria Cavalier-Smith 2002</synonym>\n<synonym datatype='string'>&quot;Deltabacteria&quot; Cavalier-Smith 1992</synonym>\n<rank>class</rank>\n<dblink><dblink-db>NCBI-TAXONOMY-DB</dblink-db>\n<dblink-oid>28221</dblink-oid>\n<dblink-relationship>unification</dblink-relationship>\n<dblink-URL>http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/Taxonomy/Browser/wwwtax.cgi?mode=Info&amp;id=28221</dblink-URL>\n</dblink>\n</Organism>\n<Organism ID='META:TAX-1236' orgid='META' frameid='TAX-1236' detail='full' class='true'><parent><Organism resource='getxml?META:TAX-1224' orgid='META' frameid='TAX-1224' class='true'/></parent>\n<common-name datatype='string'>Gammaproteobacteria</common-name>\n<synonym datatype='string'>Purple bacteria, gamma subdivision</synonym>\n<synonym datatype='string'>Pseudomonadia</synonym>\n<synonym datatype='string'>Proteobacteria gamma subdivision</synonym>\n<synonym datatype='string'>gamma subgroup</synonym>\n<synonym datatype='string'>gamma subdivision</synonym>\n<synonym datatype='string'>gamma proteobacteria</synonym>\n<rank>class</rank>\n<dblink><dblink-db>NCBI-TAXONOMY-DB</dblink-db>\n<dblink-oid>1236</dblink-oid>\n<dblink-relationship>unification</dblink-relationship>\n<dblink-URL>http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/Taxonomy/Browser/wwwtax.cgi?mode=Info&amp;id=1236</dblink-URL>\n</dblink>\n</Organism>\n<Organism ID='META:TAX-28216' orgid='META' frameid='TAX-28216' detail='full' class='true'><parent><Organism resource='getxml?META:TAX-1224' orgid='META' frameid='TAX-1224' class='true'/></parent>\n<common-name datatype='string'>Betaproteobacteria</common-name>\n<synonym datatype='string'>Purple bacteria, beta subdivision</synonym>\n<synonym datatype='string'>Proteobacteria beta subdivision</synonym>\n<synonym datatype='string'>beta subgroup</synonym>\n<synonym datatype='string'>beta subdivision</synonym>\n<synonym datatype='string'>beta proteobacteria</synonym>\n<rank>class</rank>\n<dblink><dblink-db>NCBI-TAXONOMY-DB</dblink-db>\n<dblink-oid>28216</dblink-oid>\n<dblink-relationship>unification</dblink-relationship>\n<dblink-URL>http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/Taxonomy/Browser/wwwtax.cgi?mode=Info&amp;id=28216</dblink-URL>\n</dblink>\n</Organism>\ncurl: (23) Failure writing output to destination\n","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
